<span class="displaytext"><b><em>inside the beltway, years of leading (PARTY NAME) against (PARTY NAME)s</em></b><p><b><em>"the bottom line is that i served 12 years with him, 6 years in the united states senate as leader, one of the leaders of the senate - the number-3 leader - who had the responsibility of trying to put together the conservative agenda, and almost at every turn on domestic policy, (candidate full) was not only against us, but leading the charge on the other side."</em> – former sen. rick santorum (r-pa)</b> (kathryn jean lopez, "a conservative case against (candidate last)," <em>national review</em> online, 1/14/08) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last)'s washington leadership – leading the (PARTY NAME):</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) is touting his leadership inside the beltway as a reason to support his candidacy.</b> "speaking to reporters on his bus elsewhere in florida, (candidate last) insisted his service on the senate commerce committee is better preparation for overseeing the u.s. economy than (candidate last)'s work as a business consultant, venture capitalist and olympics ceo." (glen johnson, "gop candidates tout economic skills," <em>the associated press</em>, 1/26/08) </p><p><b>former sen. rick santorum (r-pa): "(candidate full) was not only against us, but leading the charge on the other side."</b> sen. santorum: "the bottom line is that i served 12 years with him, 6 years in the united states senate as leader, one of the leaders of the senate – the number-3 leader – who had the responsibility of trying to put together the conservative agenda, and almost at every turn on domestic policy, (candidate full) was not only against us, but leading the charge on the other side." (kathryn jean lopez, "a conservative case against (candidate last)," <em>national review</em> online, 1/14/08) </p><p><b> <u>leadership? opposing the bush tax cuts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) took the lead with (PARTY NAME) opposing president bush's 2001 and 2003 tax cuts.</b> "on taxes and spending, mr. (candidate last) ... has been disingenuous in explaining his opposition to mr. bush's 2001 and 2003 tax cuts. he claims to have cast these votes to protest the fact that the tax cuts were not accompanied by spending cuts. but the fact is that in opposing these measures, mr. (candidate last) joined liberal (PARTY NAME) like sens. jay rockefeller and tom daschle in employing class-warfare rhetoric and pushing in favor of higher taxes - voting on the pro-tax side on 14 different occasions." (editorial, "(candidate last) vs. (candidate last)," <em>the washington times</em>, 1/25/08) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- club for growth president pat toomey: sen. (candidate last) opposed the "most important pro-growth tax cuts in a generation."</b> "when the most important pro-growth tax cuts in a generation were proposed by president george w. bush in 2001 and 2003, sen. (candidate last) vigorously opposed them." (pat toomey, op-ed, "the (candidate last) record," <em>the wall street journal</em>, 3/13/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>leadership? (candidate last)-kennedy immigration:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) took the lead with sen. ted kennedy (d-ma) on immigration reform, which many conservatives derided as "amnesty."</b> "on illegal immigration, mr. (candidate last) said that anyone who says he supported amnesty is 'a liar' and says he has 'never' supported social security benefits for illegals. however, in 2006 and 2007, he joined with ted kennedy to support senate bills that would have granted amnesty to millions of illegals. in 2006, mr. (candidate last) denounced in a floor speech and cast the deciding vote against an amendment by sen. john ensign, nevada (PARTY NAME), that would have denied social security benefits to illegals who work under a social security number obtained through identity fraud." (editorial, "(candidate last) vs. (candidate last)," <em>the washington times</em>, 1/25/08) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- <em>national review</em>: (candidate last)'s immigration proposal amounts to amnesty.</b> "supporters of the (candidate last)/kennedy proposal deny that it is an amnesty, pointing to the fact that payment of a (modest) fine is one of the prerequisites of legalization. but since the goal of an illegal immigrant is to work in the united states, anything that legalizes his presence is a reward; the putative fine is little more than a retroactive smuggling fee paid to the u.s. government." (editorial, "hope over experience," <em>national review</em>, 5/17/05) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>leadership? (candidate last)-feingold campaign finance reform:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) took the lead with sen. russ feingold (d-wi) on campaign finance reform, which many conservatives said violated the first amendment.</b> "another issue where mr. (candidate last) has clashed with conservatives was over campaign finance reform, also called the (candidate last)-feingold bill, which instituted a series of regulations that limit the ability of independent groups not associated with the (PARTY NAME) or (PARTY NAME) parties to participate in the political process. these regulations, which violate the first amendment, bar the use of corporate or union money to pay for broadcast advertising that identifies a federal candidate within 30 days of a primary or nominating convention or within 60 days of a general election. ... (candidate last)'s advocacy of the legislation has created a bitter political divide between the senator and the national right to life committee, which views it as a hindrance to its ability to get its message out." (editorial, "(candidate last) vs. (candidate last)," <em>the washington times</em>, 1/25/08) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- former speaker newt gingrich: (candidate last)-feingold a "dangerous modern-day assault on the first amendment."</b> "the (candidate last)-feingold campaign-finance law enacted in 2002 is an equally dangerous modern-day assault on the first amendment. it could more accurately be called the (candidate last)-feingold censorship law because it stifles political speech, protects incumbent politicians and consolidates power in washington. this law is of the congress, by the congress, and for the congress, because it protects members of congress by silencing opposing points of view." (newt gingrich, op-ed, "blacking out speech," <em>national review</em>, 6/1/06) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>leadership? (candidate last)-lieberman climate change legislation: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>sen. (candidate last) took the lead with sen. joe lieberman (d-ct) on environmental legislation, which many conservatives say will hurt the economy.</b> "mr. (candidate last) also differs with free-market conservatives on numerous environmental issues. he opposes oil drilling in the arctic national wildlife refuge (anwr) in alaska and has joined with sen. joe lieberman to cosponsor legislation that would require that greenhouse gas emissions be reduced to 2000 levels by 2010 - a measure sure to result in substantial increases in electricity and gasoline costs." (editorial, "(candidate last) vs. (candidate last)," <em>the washington times</em>, 1/25/08) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- john locke foundation's roy cordato: (candidate last)-lieberman "would dramatically raise the tax on all carbon-based fuels."</b> "what is not widely understood is that [(candidate last)] is currently sponsoring legislation that, in the name of fighting global warming, would dramatically raise the tax on all carbon-based fuels, including gasoline, home heating oil, coal, and to a lesser extent, natural gas. ... higher energy costs will, among other things, raise the cost of manufacturing big-ticket items in american factories. and higher gas prices will likely raise demand for those classes of automobiles that tend to be manufactured overseas." (roy cordato, "(candidate last)'s costly tax on energy," <em>national review</em>, www.nationalreview.com, posted 1/10/08) </p></blockquote></span>



